## Approach: BFS on States

Explore all possible states `(a, b)` where `a` = water in jug 1, `b` = water in jug 2. BFS from `(0,0)`, applying all 6 operations. Check if any state has `a == d` or `b == d` or `a + b == d`.

```javascript
function waterJugProblemUsingBfs(m, n, d) {
  if (d > m + n) return false;
  const visited = new Set(['0,0']);
  const queue = [[0, 0]];
  while (queue.length) {
    const [a, b] = queue.shift();
    if (a === d || b === d || a + b === d) return true;
    const states = [
      [m, b], [a, n], [0, b], [a, 0],
      [Math.max(0, a-(n-b)), Math.min(n, b+a)],
      [Math.min(m, a+b), Math.max(0, b-(m-a))]
    ];
    for (const [na, nb] of states) {
      const key = na + ',' + nb;
      if (!visited.has(key)) { visited.add(key); queue.push([na, nb]); }
    }
  }
  return false;
}
```

**Time Complexity:** O(m × n)
**Space Complexity:** O(m × n)

